1:# Recipe 9.2: Patient Photo Verification - Python Example
15:## Setup
36:## Config and Constants
49:# Structured logging. Never log PHI (patient names, MRNs, photos).
50:# Log patient_id references only, never the biometric data itself.
54:# Retry config for AWS API calls. Face comparison is fast but can throttle
55:# under burst load (think: 200 patients checking in at 8am Monday).
58:# --- Verification Thresholds ---
59:#
60:# SIMILARITY_THRESHOLD: minimum confidence (0-100) that two faces are the same person.
61:# Rekognition returns a similarity score for each face comparison.
62:# 95% is conservative. You'll reject some legitimate patients who look different
63:# from their enrollment photo (new glasses, weight change, aging). But you'll
64:# catch almost all mismatches.
65:#
66:# In practice, most healthcare orgs start at 90% and tune upward based on
67:# false-accept rates. The cost of a false accept (wrong patient gets treatment)
68:# is much higher than a false reject (patient re-verifies with staff).
71:# MINIMUM_FACE_CONFIDENCE: minimum confidence that Rekognition actually detected
72:# a face in the image. Below this, the image quality is too poor to trust.
75:# IMAGE_QUALITY_THRESHOLDS: brightness and sharpness minimums.
76:# Rekognition returns quality metrics for each detected face.
77:# These catch the "photo taken in a dark hallway" and "blurry selfie" cases.
81:# Maximum age (in days) for an enrollment photo before requiring re-enrollment.
82:# Faces change. A 5-year-old enrollment photo is unreliable.
85:# S3 bucket for patient photos (enrollment and verification attempts).
88:# DynamoDB table for verification audit records.
91:# Rekognition collection for indexed patient faces.
92:# Collections let you search across enrolled faces without re-uploading reference images.
98:## Step 1: Validate the Verification Image
166:## Step 2: Compare Faces
234:## Step 3: Search by Face Collection (Alternative Path)
321:## Step 4: Record the Verification Attempt
367:## Putting It All Together
